{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17598130","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17598130"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:32:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:32:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15439"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15439","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15439"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0,0.19,0.35,0.41]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8130"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63125"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8130","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8130"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15439"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48576"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8127"},{"type":"tags","id":"8746"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19710"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19713"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20610"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63125","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63125"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA particular helminth infection follows this life cycle:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEggs are ingested from contaminated soil\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELarvae penetrate the intestinal wall\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELarvae migrate through blood vessels to the liver and then lungs\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELarvae are coughed up and swallowed\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdult worms develop in the small intestine\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHeavy infections can cause intestinal obstruction\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following helminths follows this life cycle?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Trichuris trichiura","Necator americanus","Ancylostoma duodenale","Ascaris lumbricoides","Strongyloides stercoralis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAscaris lumbricoides\u003C/strong\u003E is a roundworm and the commonest parasitic infection found in humans. It is estimated that over 800 million people globally are infected with this parasite, mainly those living in the tropical and subtropical regions. Whilst various soil-borne helminths are endemic in tropical Australia, Ascaris lumbricoides is a relatively rare finding. It is spread by faeco-oral contact. The life-cycle is described in the stem of this item. Ascaris is notorious for causing intestinal obstruction due to the large size of adult worms (up to 35 cm).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003EAncylostoma duodenale\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003ENecator americanus\u003C/strong\u003E (hookworms) do migrate through the lungs, they initially penetrate through skin rather than being ingested. \u003Cstrong\u003EStrongyloides stercoralis\u003C/strong\u003E can auto-infect and has a more complex life cycle involving free-living stages.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrichuris trichiura\u003C/strong\u003E (whipworm) has a direct life cycle without tissue migration. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ascaris lumbricoides has a complex life cycle involving pulmonary migration before returning to the intestine","Ascaris infection can cause intestinal obstruction due to the large size and number of adult worms"],"references":["Kaiser L, Surawicz CM. Infectious causes of chronic diarrhoea. Best Pract Res Clin Gastroenterol. 2012 Oct;26(5):563-71. doi: 10.1016/j.bpg.2012.11.001. PMID: 23384802","DuPont HL. Persistent Diarrhea: A Clinical Review. JAMA. 2016 Jun 28;315(24):2712-23. doi: 10.1001/jama.2016.7833. PMID: 27357241.","Nemeth V, Pfleghaar N. Diarrhea. [Updated 2022 Nov 21]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK448082/","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Kaiser L, Surawicz CM. Infectious causes of chronic diarrhoea. Best Pract Res Clin Gastroenterol. 2012 Oct;26(5):563-71. doi: 10.1016/j.bpg.2012.11.001. PMID: 23384802","Sell J, Dolan B. Common Gastrointestinal Infections. Prim Care. 2018 Sep;45(3):519-532. doi: 10.1016/j.pop.2018.05.008. Epub 2018 Jul 9. PMID: 30115338"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48576"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15439"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48576","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/48576"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-20T08:28:50+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-20T08:29:14+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8130"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63125"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedic